@endnode
@node Call_1 "Command specification"
@{b}Command specification@{ub}

                                  @{b}Call@{ub}

@{i}Format:@{ui}           Call <Address> [<Redials>] [<Delay>]

@{i}Template:@{ui}         ADDRESS/A,REDIALS/N,DELAY/N

@{i}Purpose:@{ui}          To call a remote system

@{i}Specification:@{ui}

Call will dial the remote system specified by Address. By default,
it operates similarly to the original Call script. To utilize the
redialling feature, specify the amount of maximum redials, ie. the
number of call attempts made after the first call has failed. By
default the delay between two redials is two minutes, but you can
change it using the DELAY keyword.

@{i}Examples:@{ui}

Here are a few examples to clarify things.

    Call 2:220/90 REDIALS 3

This will call the system a maximum of four times (initial call and
then three redials) if a connection has not been established during
one of the previous attempts.

    Call 39:268/3 REDIALS 7 DELAY 5

Same as above, but the total number of calls is max. eight and the
delay between redials is five minutes instead of two.

Note! You may leave out the keywords and only pass the arguments.
@endnode
@node Call_2 "Installing"
@{b}Installing@{ub}

You need to update the WPL script s:JamMail.WPL. Add the following line
in the CConnect2 code:

    System "Echo >T:SessionSuccess $(Remote.Address)"

I have it just before setting Host.Sitename. Call will know if a connection
was made by taking a look in the T: directory and see if the file is there.
@endnode
@node Call_3 "Enhancements"
@{b}Enhancements@{ub}

Since the command added to the WPL script writes the remote address
into the file, Call could be improved to check the it against the address
it was dialling to see if the remote system was the same one.
@endnode
